{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"46afc0a1-4e5a-42a8-ab59-5ca1a6cd69c3","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n**1. Recursive wildcard glob (Line 9, `.csproj`)**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` glob forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is expensive at scale and re-evaluated on every build.\n\n**2. File I/O via property function (Line 13, `.csproj`)**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs synchronous disk I/O in the critical path. This blocks the evaluator and defeats caching.\n\n**3. Deeply chained imports (level1 → level2 → level3)**\nThree levels of nested `<Import>` files that each import the next create a long sequential evaluation chain. While each file is trivial here, this pattern becomes costly as content grows — each level must fully evaluate before the parent can continue.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of recommendations:**\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow the glob or move to a target (lazy eval) |\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | Move to a target with `ReadLinesFromFile` task |\n| Chained imports | Flatten into a single `.props` or reduce nesting |\n\nThe most impactful fix is removing the property-function file read and narrowing the wildcard glob — both execute unconditionally on every evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ca88faf-a8ea-4bc1-b736-bfc3a9c1206e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":432,"requestId":"F01E:E284D:2752A0E:2B901A1:69F9452C"},"id":"ad63f200-b813-4b65-8d94-08e4c0624768","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:17:43.394Z","parentId":"5fcd694f-4a3a-4549-bdeb-773ae5a01615"}
